  <static seed="1320" source="Contrib/PCC/Math95/ComplexFractions/ComplexFractions2.pg">
    <statement><p>Simplify this expression.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\frac{{\frac{xy^{2}}{4z}}}{{\frac{x}{2yz}}}=}</m><fillin characters="40" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\frac{y^{3}}{2}</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>To simply the complex fraction <m>\frac{{\frac{xy^{2}}{4z}}}{{\frac{x}{2yz}}}</m>, we multiple the numerator and denominator with the common denominator of <m>{\frac{xy^{2}}{4z}}</m> and <m>{\frac{x}{2yz}}</m>, which is <m>{4yz}</m>.</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}
  \frac{{\frac{xy^{2}}{4z}}}{{\frac{x}{2yz}}} \amp = \frac{{\frac{xy^{2}}{4z}}\cdot{4yz}}{{\frac{x}{2yz}}\cdot{4yz}} \\
    \amp = {\frac{y^{3}}{2}}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>Note that you are not required to enter lost domain conditions in this problem, but it<rsq/>s good to know the following.</p>
<p>Since <m>y</m> and <m>z</m> were canceled, <m>y \ne 0</m> and <m>z \ne 0</m> are in the lost domain condition.</p>
</solution>
